\r\n- Copy the &#39;code&#39; from Week 2 <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?page=189&action=edit\">from here</a></br/>\r\n- Create a new page by <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=page&action=edit\">clicking here</a></br/>\r\n- paste the copied &#39;code&#39; into the code text area. In that code, change all instances of &#39;week2&#39; to &#39;weekn&#39; where &#39;n&#39; is the current week. And change all instances of &#39;Zoraini&#39; to the current presenter&#39;s name.</br/>\r\n- Type a title into the title field</br/>\r\n- type a location: weekn.htm into the location field (eg., week05.htm or week11.htm)</br/>\r\n- type &#39;page_header&#39; and &#39;page_footer&#39; into the header and footer fields respectively.</br/>\r\n- press &#39;submit&#39;</br/></br/></li>\r\n\r\n\r\n<li><i>Create an announcement</i><br/>\r\n- This is where we (the course administrators) introduce the new week, our presenter, and the topic. It is in our voice, not the presenter&#39;s. Keep it short; you don&#39;t need to link to a bunch of stuff here, that&#39;s all done below.<br/>\r\n- Create a new post by <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=post&action=edit\">clicking here</a></br/>\r\n- Select &#39;announcement&#39; from the &#39;Type&#39; dropdown<br/>\r\n- Give the post a &#39;Title&#39; and type a short message into &#39;Description&#39;<br/>\r\n- <u><i>Important</i></u>: put the tag &#39;weekn&#39; (eg., week5) somewhere in the description. (Yes, I know it&#39;s not elegant; I will code a better solution soon).<br/>\r\n- click &#39;submit&#39;<br/><br/></li>\r\n\r\n<li><i>Create the presenter&#39;s article post</i><br/>\r\n- This is the presenter&#39;s own contribution, and should be in the presenter&#39;s voice, not ours.<br/>\r\n- Create a new post by <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=post&action=edit\">clicking here</a></br/>\r\n- select &#39;article&#39; from the &#39;Type&#39; dropdown</br/>\r\n- enter a title, something like: \"Week 15: Fred Presenter on Widgets\"</br/>\r\n- type or paste a opne-paragraph summary into the &#39;description&#39; field</br/>\r\n- put the rest of the content into the &#39;content&#39; field</br/>\r\n- <u><i>Important</i></u>: put the tag &#39;weekn&#39; (eg., week5) somewhere in the description<br/>\r\n- press &#39;submit&#39;<br/>\r\n- Optional: Note that you can use this form to upload attachments, such as documents, MP3 audio, or images</br/></br/></li>\r\n\r\n<li><i>Schedule the speaker&#39;s presentation event</i><br/>\r\n- Create a new event by <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=event&action=edit\">clicking here</a></br/>\r\n- Give the event a title in &#39;Title&#39; and enter the presenter&#39;s name in &#39;star&#39;</br/>\r\n- Enter the following in &#39;link&#39;: http://change.mooc.ca/meetings.htm</br/>\r\n- Enter the start and finish time - use the little calendar to pick the date and time</br/>\r\n- <u><i>Important</i></u>: put the current week (eg., week3) into the &#39;identifier&#39; element</br/></br/></li>\r\n\r\n<li><i>Create publication records</i></br/>\r\n- a &#39;publication&#39; is anything formally published, like a book or an article in an academic journal or magazine. Enter as many publications as you want.</br/>\r\n- Create a new publication entry by <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=publication&action=edit\">clicking here</a></br/>\r\n- Type values for &#39;Title&#39;, &#39;Author Name&#39;, &#39;Journal Name&#39;, &#39;Volume&#39;, &#39;Pages&#39; and &#39;Publisher Name&#39;. </br/>\r\n- Enter a one-paragraph summary of the publication in &#39;Description&#39;<br/>\r\n- <u><i>Important</i></u>: put the tag &#39;weekn&#39; (eg., week5) somewhere in the description<br/>\r\n- In &#39;Link&#39; paste the link the publication may be found or retrieved</br/>\r\n- Don&#39;t worry about the rest of the fields; just hit submit</br/></br/></li>\r\n\r\n<li><i>Create new presentation records</i></br/>\r\n- A presentation is a set of slides, video of a talk, or some such thing typically involving embedded media. Enter as many as you want.</br/>\r\n- Create a new presentation by <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=presentation&action=edit\">clicking here</a></br/>\r\n- Enter values for &#39;Title&#39;, &#39;Author&#39;, &#39;Conference&#39;, etc.</br/>\r\n- In &#39;Link&#39;, enter the URL to the presentation site or conference site</br/>\r\n- In &#39;Location&#39;, enter the physical location of the presentation, eg., &#39;New York&#39;, or if it was online, enter &#39;Online&#39;</br/>\r\n- In &#39;Slides&#39; enter the URL where slides can be found - the actual .ppt link</br/>\r\n- In &#39;Audio&#39; enter the URL where audio MP3 can be found - the actual .mp3 link</br/>\r\n- In &#39;Video&#39; enter the URL where video can be found - the actual .mp4 (or .mov, etc) link</br/>\r\n- Enter a summary of the presentation in &#39;Description&#39;</br/>\r\n- <u><i>Important</i></u>: put the tag &#39;weekn&#39; (eg., week5) somewhere in the description<br/>\r\n- In &#39;Slide player&#39; enter the embed code from Slideshare or Prexi or Scribd - you don&#39;t need to change the embed code at all, just paste it in</br/>\r\n- In &#39;Video player&#39; enter the embed code from YouTube or Vimeo or whatever - again, you don&#39;t need to change it, just paste it in</br/>\r\n- Ignore &#39;audio player&#39;, we have a nifty player for MP3 files (unless the *only* way to provide access to audio is to embed a player)</br/>\r\n- click &#39;submit&#39;</br/></br/></li>\r\n\r\n<li><i>Create posts</i>\r\n- For everything else, create a post. Create new post by <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=post&action=edit\">Clicking here</a></br/>\r\n- select &#39;Link&#39; from the &#39;Type&#39; dropdown (that&#39;s the default)</br/>\r\n- Enter values for &#39;Title&#39; and &#39;Description&#39;</br/>\r\n- <u><i>Important</i></u>: put the tag &#39;weekn&#39; (eg., week5) somewhere in the description<br/>\r\n- Enter the author name under &#39;Author&#39; (not your name unless you&#39;re linking to something you created)</br/>\r\n- Enter the name of the weblog, publication, or website in &#39;Journal&#39;</br/>\r\n- Provide a direct link to the resource in &#39;Link&#39;</br/>\r\n- press &#39;submit</br/></br/></li>\r\n\r\n<li><i>Verify your page:</i><br/>\r\n- You can now verify that the page looks ok. <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=page&action=list&number=100\">Click here</a> to list all pages. Your page (titled &#39;Week whatever&#39;) will be near the bottom of the list, in its proper place<br />\r\n- To preview the page, first click [Edit] next to the page name, then click [View Generated Version of Page] in the page editing screen. You should see all the content you entered displayed on the page.<br/>\r\n- Back-space from the preview back to the edit screen, then publish the page by clicking [Publish Page]<br/>\r\n- Go back to the list if pages <a href=\"http://change.mooc.ca/cgi-bin/admin.cgi?db=page&action=list&number=100\">here</a> and click [Publish] beside important course pages, such as the index page (but not the newsletter page; that is handled separately).<br/><br/></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br/>\r\n<p>Note: all of this content will also be displayed in the newsletter for the day. Content submitted on the weekend will appear in Monday&#39;s newsletter.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Friday','<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC \"-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Strict//EN\"\r\n    \"http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-strict.dtd\">\r\n<html xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" xml:lang=\"en\" lang=\"en-AU\">\r\n\r\n<!-- mooc.ca template page_header -->\r\n\r\n<head>\r\n\r\n<!-- title -->\r\n  <title>Setting Up a New Week ~ #change11</title>\r\n\r\n<!-- scripts -->\r\n  <script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"http://change.mooc.ca/js/downes.js\"></script>\r\n  <script type=\"text/javascr